.TH pif 1  "pif 0.2.8" 
.SH NAME
pif \- PIF \- A CLI package manager for interactive fiction languages
.SH SYNOPSIS
\fBpif\fR [\fB\-s\fR|\fB\-\-system\fR] [\fB\-\-color\fR] [\fB\-v\fR|\fB\-\-verbose\fR] [\fB\-h\fR|\fB\-\-help\fR] [\fB\-V\fR|\fB\-\-version\fR] <\fIsubcommands\fR>
.SH DESCRIPTION
pif is a package manager for interactive fiction extension libraries.
.PP
It maintains a local copy of the IF extensions registry (refreshed with `pif update`) and lets you browse, install, and manage libraries for TADS 3, Inform 7, Inform 6, Dialog, Hugo, ZIL, and other IF authoring systems.
.PP
WORKFLOW
.PP
  1. pif update          — download the latest registry index
  2. pif list            — browse available extensions
  3. pif install <name>  — install an extension into the system\*(Aqs directory
  4. pif info <name>     — view full metadata and version history
.PP
SYSTEMS
.PP
Extensions are tagged with the IF system they target. pif auto\-detects the system from files in the current directory:
.PP
  Makefile / .t3m   → tads3
  .inf              → inform6
  .i7x / .materials → inform
  .dg               → dialog
  .hug              → hugo
.PP
Override detection with \-\-system, or use \-\-system=all to work across every known system at once.
.PP
CONFIGURATION
.PP
Per\-system install directories, verbosity, and version constraints are stored in the pif config file:
.PP
  Linux/macOS  $XDG_CONFIG_HOME/pif/config.yaml  (usually ~/.config/pif/)
  Windows      %APPDATA%\\pif\\config.yaml
.PP
Manage the config with the `pif config` subcommand.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB\-s\fR, \fB\-\-system\fR \fI<SYSTEM>\fR [default: auto]
IF system to target (default: auto\-detect from current directory)

pif inspects the current directory for recognised file extensions and picks the most likely system:

Makefile / .t3m   → tads3 .inf              → inform6 .i7x / .materials → inform .dg               → dialog .hug              → hugo .zil              → zil

Use \-\-system=all to list or install across every known system at once.
.br

.br
\fIPossible values:\fR
.RS 14
.IP \(bu 2
auto
.IP \(bu 2
all
.IP \(bu 2
tads3
.IP \(bu 2
tads2
.IP \(bu 2
dialog
.IP \(bu 2
inform
.IP \(bu 2
inform6
.IP \(bu 2
hugo
.IP \(bu 2
zil
.IP \(bu 2
unknown
.RE
.TP
\fB\-\-color\fR \fI<COLOR>\fR [default: auto]
Colour output control

auto   — use colour when stdout is a terminal (default) always — force colour even when piped never  — disable colour entirely
.br

.br
\fIPossible values:\fR
.RS 14
.IP \(bu 2
always
.IP \(bu 2
auto
.IP \(bu 2
never
.RE
.TP
\fB\-v\fR, \fB\-\-verbose\fR \fI<VERBOSE>\fR [default: 2]
Verbosity level (1–3)

1 — errors and warnings only 2 — normal output (default) 3 — detailed / debug output

The default can be changed permanently with `pif config verbose set`.
.TP
\fB\-h\fR, \fB\-\-help\fR
Print help (see a summary with \*(Aq\-h\*(Aq)
.TP
\fB\-V\fR, \fB\-\-version\fR
Print version
.SH SUBCOMMANDS
.TP
pif\-info(1)
Show information about an extension
.TP
pif\-update(1)
Fetch the latest extension registry from upstream
.TP
pif\-install(1)
Install one or more extensions
.TP
pif\-list(1)
List available extensions
.TP
pif\-publish(1)
Publish an extension to the pif index
.TP
pif\-tags(1)
List all available tags
.TP
pif\-search(1)
Search extensions by name and description
.TP
pif\-config(1)
Manage pif configuration
.TP
pif\-registry(1)
Manage the local extension registry
.TP
pif\-help(1)
Print this message or the help of the given subcommand(s)
